          <td bgcolor="" valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
  <tr>
    <td>
      <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
        <tr>
          <td>
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">
              <tr> 
                <td class="chpurple"><font class="h1font"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3"><tr><td><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Optimizing Your Deck<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.71)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=13823'>Edward "Special Ed" Cunningham</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=13823&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 20, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont">     Wonder why you never seem to get the right cards at the right time?  Or how your opponent always seems to have what he or she needs?  Optimizing the cards in your deck ensures that you always have what&#39;s best at any given time.<br />
<br />
    The first item on the deck optimizing agenda is to look at your magi&#39;s starting cards, your first magi&#39;s in particular.  Choosing which cards to use on your first magi is that hardest because getting them won&#39;t give you any card advantage.  On later magi you should almost always have any starting cards in your deck that are even remotely useful as you get to retrieve them for free.  But since your first magi always gets a 5 card hand, getting starting cards is only advantageous if they give you more benefit than other cards in the deck.<br />
<br />
    When you choose your opening magi&#39;s starting cards you should first look at what type of deck, and what type of magi you have.  Do you rely on getting certain combos out, and the sooner the better?  Do want to stall for as long as possible until you have the right cards for your next magi?  Are you simply trying to get a big hand and then speedily reveal your second magi?  Or are you just trying to create an advantage right off the bat?  <br />
<br />
    Let&#39;s take a look at some of the most popular starting magi and determine what&#39;s best to get for them.  Delia is probably Arderial&#39;s most popular and best starter.  She adds one to all Vellups and energizes for 6, so she&#39;s got great inherent energy advantage.  Then you get to pull more Vellups from your deck and recur them from your graveyard, meaning you virtually don&#39;t have to play cards from your hand at all.  This allows you to build up both a card advantage and an energy advantage.  The Vellup is the only one of her starting cards she needs unless you have specific plans for the shooting star (i.e. Vellup-Elder Vellup-Xyx Minor, shooting star the Minor and then Gathering Clouds him up to 6).  Many Naroom players use Tiller first.  His strategy is not quite as simple as Delia&#39;s.  Getting the Weebo and Weeblit is obvious, but many people use the Vortex of Knowledge as well.  The VoK only gains you card advantage if you go first (as your opponent will always get a 5 card hand whether or not they already have cards in hand at the beginning of their first turn).  Kazm is a good example of a magi with starting cards you definitely don&#39;t want all of.  Of his 4 starting cards the only ones worth pulling are the Giant Baldar (to ensure that your opponent must trigger Hunter) and the Cleansing (but only if you have Core cards in your deck that you need to Cleanse).  The rest of them don&#39;t guarantee you an advantage, and that&#39;s what this article is all about.<br />
<br />
    The next target for deck optimization is size.  Many people favor decks over 40 cards with the rationalization that they make up for it in card draw capabilities.  This is an inherently flawed argument if you simply look at the game from a probability standpoint.  The larger the deck, the less likely you are to get your optimal hand.  If you don&#39;t agree with this statement, look at your deck and determine what your best reasonable hand is at any point in the game.  This means decide which 5 card opening hand is best, how many cards you&#39;re likely to have going into your second and third magi and what cards are best to have then.  Any cards that didn&#39;t appear in those lists should probably be dropped from the deck.  If you still can&#39;t decide what should go, try to pick the worst starting hand you could have.  What cards just can&#39;t be played on your first turn, or won&#39;t likely give you an advantage?<br />
<br />
  After you get your deck down to 40 cards look at the average casting cost of the cards in your deck.  Ideally the average should be half your average magi&#39;s energize rate.  This means for most decks your average casting cost should be between 2 and 3.  Having a low average cost means you&#39;ll most likely be able to play both of the cards you draw each turn.  Only being able to play one card a turn off your magi&#39;s energize rate greatly reduces your options.<br />
<br />
Lastly, you need to determine if your deck is primarily  reactive (control type) or active(beat down).  Active decks should mostly contain active cards.  Active cards are cards that give you some type of advantage the turn you play them.  Most spells are active, as are most creatures with powers that can be used the turn you play them.  In Magi-Nation you pretty much only have 2 kinds of advantages: cards and energy.  If you use an active deck, then as many of your cards as possible should either gain you an energy advantage immediately or gain you cards immediately.  Passive decks are much harder to use.  The most common ones are Underneath with burrowing and Weave with all their reactive effects.  Passive decks need to be able to get the cards they need for their combos, either by drawing a lot of cards early, or by stalling for a long time.  Once they have their combo out they need to be able to protect it.  Anything that&#39;s not part of the combo or card draw to get the combo should probably be control or removal elements to ensure that your opponent can&#39;t break your strategy.<br />
<br />
Hopefully these ideas are interesting and helpful for you.  I could go on for days with specific examples of cards that are and aren&#39;t optimal, but there simply isn&#39;t space for it here.  If you have any questions or comments on this article please d-mail me or leave reviews.<br />
